AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;A video posted by Donald Trump's Truth Social account shows hypothetical titles that speak of a "Unified Reich" if he were to win the presidential election of 2024> - a language that attracted harsh criticism from the campaign of President Joe Biden. >
&nbsp;
"What will happen after Donald Trump's victory? What will happen after Donald Trump's victory?", he asks for a voice out of field in the 30-second clip, showing a series of fictitious titles on American prosperity. Among a series of titles, including "Economic boom!" and "The frontier is closed", one mentions "the creation of a unified Reich".
<br In the clip no direct reference is made to the Nazis, but the word "reich" is commonly used in reference to the Third Reich of Nazi Germany, led by Adolf Hitler. Other references in the video, which seems to have multiple text pieces copied and glued to fill the background of the "journal", mention the First World War >. The title "Unified Reich" seems to refer to the unification of Germany of 1871. Politico reported that a Trump staff did not see the word "reich" before posting the video.
&nbsp;
The former leader repeatedly tried to portray Biden as unable to restrain anti-Semitism in the United States > during a period of increasing tensions fueled by the war in Gaza. Trump himself faced criticism for calling for a Nazi rhetoric, including having repeatedly talked about immigrants as "parasites" that are "swing blood" in the United States. In 2017, as president, Trump described some neo-Nazi marchers during the violent protests of Charlottesville, Virginia, who shouted the slogan "Jews will not replace us", as "very beautiful people" and dined with white nationalists in his Florida estate.
&nbsp;
Trump has a "long history" of anti-Semitic behavior, says Biden's campaign in a harsh statement in response to the video. "Donald Trump is not playing. He is telling America exactly what he intends to do if he regains power: to rule as a dictator on a unified 'reich', said Biden-Harris spokesman James Singer.<br> "Speaking to parrot of the 'Mein Kampf' while warning of a bloodbath in case of defeat is the type of undesirable behavior that is obtained by a man who knows that democracy continues to refuse its extreme vision of chaos, division and violence."

