AGI - More than 30 thousand people died in the United Kingdom > between the 1970s and 1990s after receiving transfusions of &nbsp;sangue&nbsp; infect > from viruses such as HIV or hepatitis but the authorities covered the scandal. A report made public today by Infected Blood Inquiry. Among the victims there are thousands of people who had been injured in accidents or suffering from diseases of the &nbsp;sangue&nbsp; or were subjected to surgical interventions requiring transfusions of &nbsp; blood; among them also numerous children > About three thousand "infected" died immediately, others later: This is, according to the conclusions of the investigation, the "most great therapeutic disaster in the eighty years of history of the National Health Service (NHS). The long-awaited relationship, along more than 2,500 pages, has bare a "catalogue of failures" with "catastrophic" consequences for the victims and their loved ones. "A large part, though not entirely, could have been avoided," said Judge Brian Langstaff.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The team led by Langstaff verified that the governments and health workers who succeeded did not manage to reduce the risks despite the fact that it was evident at the beginning of the 1980s that AIDS could be transmitted through the &nbsp;sangue&nbsp;infetto>. The donors of &nbsp;sangue&nbsp; were not properly controlled and blood products were also imported from abroad, and in particular from the United States, where drug addicts and prisoners were used for donations. Moreover, too many transfusions were carried out even when they were not necessarily necessary, according to the report. The evidence of attempts to hide the scandal has also been found, with the destruction of documents by officials of the health department in 1993.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
According to the report, "the answer to the question: Was there a cover-up? Not in the sense of a handful of people who plot into an orchestrated conspiracy to mislead, but in a subtler, more pervasive and more chilling way in its implications." Langstaff said that "the scope of what happened is terrifying" and that the suffering of people was aggravated by repeated denials and false assurances that they had received good health treatment. When the victims were told the truth, sometimes years later, that was done insensitively and inappropriately. "What I found out was that the disaster wasn't an accident. People put their trust in doctors and government and that trust was betrayed," Langstaff said at a press conference, recommending that victims be compensated. Tomorrow, the government should announce a package worth about £10 billion for this purpose. The investigation, one of the most clamorous in the UK, was launched in 2017 by the then first ministra Theresa May.&nbsp;

